article.description:
Yolanda Griffith had 27 points, 11 rebounds and five steals, carrying the Sacramento Monarchs to a 65-56 win over
the Phoenix Mercury on Thursday night.
article.headline: Phoenix has no answer for Griffith's power game
article.linkText: Griffith owns Phoenix inside as Monarchs roll to win
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Yolanda Griffith felt worn down during
Sacramento's opener. Everybody should play that well when they're
tired.

	   Griffith had 27 points, 11 rebounds and five steals, carrying
the Monarchs to a 65-56 win over the Phoenix Mercury on Thursday
night.

	   "I'll let them know if I need a break,'' said Griffith, who
played 36 minutes. "I was a little tired toward the end, yes, but
I felt like they needed me. Sometimes you have to tough it out.''

	   Edna Campbell added 13 points and Tangela Smith scored 11 for
the Monarchs, who won 11 of their last 14 in 2002 and opened this
season with a win.

	   The Mercury's Edwina Brown had 15 points and Tamicha Jackson 13,
but Brown was 4-for-14 from the floor, and Jackson was 6-for-21 as
Phoenix shot 31.3 percent.

	   Coach John Shumate attributed part of that to the new makeup of
his team -- only four players were with the Mercury last year.

	   "It's a matter of learning to play with each other -- knowing
where someone likes to pass, knowing their habits,'' Shumate said.
"I thought we had good shots and good looks. We just didn't make
the shots that I thought we could.''

	   None of Phoenix's inside players were close to double figures in
any category, and Griffith, who led the WNBA in offensive rebounds
last year, had six under her own basket -- several at crucial points
in the game.

	   "She's one of the greatest players in the world,'' Monarchs
coach Maura McHugh said. "She made some monster rebounds for us.''

	   The Monarchs couldn't get their lead above nine points until
Campbell made a pair of free throws for a 65-55 lead with 34
seconds to play. But Phoenix never led, with Griffith making
several key baskets.

	   She stopped a Phoenix run early in the second half with a layup,
two free throws and a turnaround, opening a 52-45 lead with 10:10
remaining.

	   After another Mercury surge, Griffith made two free throws and a
layup after picking up a loose ball. The basket put Sacramento
ahead 60-53 with 4:45 to go.

	   "Yolanda Griffith was crazy on the boards, but I think we
expected that,'' Jackson said. "We expected her to come in and get
a double-double. But that wasn't as crucial as our shooting down
the stretch.''

	   Griffith had 17 points at halftime, including six in the final
56 seconds, to give the Monarchs a 37-32 lead.

	   Her first basket opened a 13-4 lead 4:54 into the game, but
Plenette Pierson had seven points during a surge by the Mercury,
and Anna DeForge tied it at 17 with a short jumper with 7:33 to go.

	   It was also knotted at 19 and 21 before Smith broke the last tie
with a layup and added a 3-pointer, opening a 26-21 lead with 4:48
to go.

	   "It was halfway decent game for us,'' Campbell said. "We
realized a lot of our weaknesses this game and things that we need
to work on, but we're happy to get a win besides not playing up to
par.''
